  "prompt": "How much of myoglobin is there in pork and how much of Iron is there in the myoglobin in weight?",
  "response": "Myoglobin is a protein found in muscle tissue that binds oxygen and gives meat its red color. The amount of myoglobin in pork (or any meat) depends on the muscle type, with muscles that are used more frequently containing higher levels of myoglobin. Pork is generally considered a \"white meat,\" but it still contains myoglobin. \n\n### **Myoglobin Content in Pork:**\nOn average, pork contains about **2-3 mg of myoglobin per gram of muscle tissue**. This can vary depending on the specific muscle and activity level of the animal.\n\n### **Iron Content in Myoglobin:**\nMyoglobin contains **one iron atom per molecule**, which is part of the heme group that binds oxygen. The molecular weight of myoglobin is approximately **17,000 Daltons (Da)**, and one iron atom has an atomic weight of **55.85 Daltons (Da)**.\n\nTo calculate the weight percentage of iron in myoglobin:\n1. Iron weight per myoglobin molecule: **55.85 Da**\n2. Total myoglobin molecular weight: **17,000 Da**\n\nThe weight percentage of iron in myoglobin is:\n\\[\n\\text{Weight \\% of Iron} = \\frac{55.85}{17,000} \\times 100 \\approx 0.33\\%\n\\]\n\n### **Practical Example:**\nIf 100 grams of pork contains **200 mg of myoglobin**, the iron content from myoglobin would be:\n\\[\n\\text{Iron} = 200 \\, \\text{mg} \\times 0.33\\% = 0.66 \\, \\text{mg of iron}\n\\]\n\nThis iron is part of the heme iron, which is more bioavailable than non-heme iron from plant sources.\n\n### **Summary:**\n- Pork typically contains **2-3 mg of myoglobin per gram of muscle tissue**.\n- Myoglobin is **0.33% iron by weight**.\n- In 100 grams of pork, the iron from myoglobin is approximately **0.66 mg** (assuming 200 mg of myoglobin).\n\nLet me know if you'd like further clarification!",
